A 14-year-old girl and 16-year-old boy found out they have been living with diabetes during a medical camp in Busia last Saturday. Joseph Mwangi from the Kenya Diabetes and Management Information Centre said the two were among 40 people who tested positive for diabetes during the screening at Busia Polytechnic. The drive was sponsored by the Safaricom Foundation in collaboration witht eh county. “It could be the two are from families with a history of diabetes. It could also be due to an allergy that infects the pancreas, eating and drinking habits or smoking cigarettes,” he said. People with eye and teeth problems turned out in large numbers . Twenty-one people with cataracts were referred for surgery at the Busia Referral Hospital. Residents were urged to go for regular checkups. Click here for the latest political news